This happens because you set `UITabBarViewControllerDelegate` only in `viewWillAppear` method. So first time there is no delegate&#39;s call, view appears, sets delegate and involves `func tabBarController(_ tabBarController: UITabBarController, shouldSelect viewController: UIViewController) -&gt; Bool` method only on following taps.

**UPD:**

By the way, are you sure that this particular controller should be a delegate for `UITabBarController`? Is it correct that concrete controller decides which tab could be opened and which not? In a simple app I would assign to delegate tab bar controller itself:

```
final class TabBarVC: UITabBarController {
    override func viewDidLoad() {
        super.viewDidLoad()
        delegate = self
    }
}

extension TabBarVC: UITabBarControllerDelegate {
    func tabBarController(_ tabBarController: UITabBarController, shouldSelect viewController: UIViewController) -&gt; Bool {
       // do your logic here
    }
}
```

Of course, you should specify, that your current tab bar controller is type of `TabBarVC`.

